&gt; your e-mail you comment that &quot;other people have their unique
connections
&gt; to the letters.&quot; This ignores the fact that the manual does not
&gt; authorize &quot;unique connections&quot; in forming the letters. When one letter
&gt; that ends where another starts, one does not have to make a pen-lift.
&gt; When they do not end at the same point, a pen-lift should always be
made
&gt; because the shape of the QS letters are simpler than T.O. and
additional
&gt; connecting lines added willy-nilly at the writer&#39;s whim will
inevitably
&gt; cause legibility to suffer. One should not make connecting lines
&gt; between letters that do not join naturally. To do so is to revert back
&gt; to the practices of writing in Roman.
&gt; 
&gt; Shavian Script is best printed as it is quite clear.
&gt; 
&gt; The meaning of the preceding sentence is unclear to me. Shavian is a
&gt; script with no connections between letters so what does &quot;best printed&quot;
&gt; mean? It only has what we term a &quot;printed&quot; form, i.e. no cursive form
&gt; of Shavian exists.
&gt; 
&gt; &gt; From: stbett
&gt; &gt; Sent: 8/31/2002 8:01:08 AM
&gt; &gt; To: Read_Alphabet@yahoogroups.com
&gt; &gt; Subject: [Read_Alphabet] Re: NBC English - oh, and Hi everyone
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Hi Grant, welcome to the group.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Issue #1: Shouldn&#39;t the base dialect be more neutral?
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Just because there is a base dialect does not mean that you have to
&gt; &gt; speak that way. It does mean that you have to be familiar with the
&gt; &gt; dialect if that is the basis of standardized spelling.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; snip...
&gt; &gt; It will be much easier for all to phonemically spell as an NBC
&gt; &gt; commentator speaks than as Queen Elizabeth spoke. I don&#39;t think the
&gt; &gt; issue is proper pronunciation. It is more a case of a pronunciation
&gt; &gt; that will be widely understood.
&gt; 
&gt; Everyone seems convinced that the use of QS or Shavian will require a
&gt; standardized spelling, which I feel is a hangover from the current
&gt; situation with T.O. I remain unconvinced. In my opinion, as soon as
&gt; you standardize the spelling, and people pronounce the words in the
way
&gt; they are accustomed to, the alphabet stops being a relatively accurate
&gt; representation of speech and over time the divergence between spoken
&gt; English and written English will inevitably increase, and given enough
&gt; time, we will be back in the same boat we are in now. If we would keep
&gt; the spoken and written forms closely together, then some group would
&gt; have to be given authority to change the &quot;official&quot; spelling of words,
&gt; and the English-speaking world has no such group.
&gt; 
&gt; If I, as an American, can understand Australian English or British
&gt; English when spoken, I surely should be able to understand it when
&gt; written in QS. In fact, I corresponded with an New Zealand native in
QS
&gt; in 1974 and had absolutely no problem understanding what he had
written,
&gt; and we had no &quot;standardized spelling.&quot;
&gt; 
&gt; Really obscure English dialects will probably not appear in print that
&gt; often in any event, and, if they did, and people could not comprehend
&gt; them, presumably the authors of such works would learn about that in
&gt; short order and make the necessary changes to alter their orthography
to
&gt; the closest main-stream dialect.
